<p></p>.<p>Confusion is a change in mental status in which a person is not able to think 
with his or her usual level of clarity. Frequently, confusion leads to the loss 
of ability to recognize people and or places, or tell time and the date. Feelings of 
disorientation are common in confusion, and decision-making ability is impaired.
</p>.<p>Confusion may arise suddenly or develop gradually over time. Confusion has 
multiple causes, including injuries, medical conditions, medications, 
environmental factors, and <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/drug_abuse/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">substance abuse</a>.</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>Kasper, D.L., et al., eds. <i>Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 19th Ed</i>. United States: McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.</p>